<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1146,1892]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,408,1146,1172]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
The present taxon was earlier synonymized with the widespread, variable 
<taxonomicName authority="Ringdahl, 1959" authorityName="Ringdahl" authorityYear="1959" box="[1284,1428,1147,1172]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pseudonupedia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intersecta">
<emphasis box="[1284,1428,1147,1172]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. intersecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Griffiths" box="[197,384,1186,1212]" pageId="18" pageNumber="23" refString="Griffiths, G. C. D. (1987) Anthomyiidae [part]. In: Griffiths, G. C. D. (Ed.), Flies of the Nearctic Region, 8 (2), 6, 729 - 952. E. Schweizerbart, Stuttgart." type="journal article" year="1987">
Griffiths (
<number box="[314,375,1186,1212]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1987.0">1987</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
concluded, based on a morphometric study of the outer lamellae of male sternite V, that two distinct species are involved.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1146,1892]" box="[198,1229,1266,1292]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,1266,1292]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Description.</emphasis>
In most respects agreeing closely with 
<taxonomicName authority="Ringdahl, 1959" authorityName="Ringdahl" authorityYear="1959" box="[813,957,1267,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pseudonupedia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intersecta">
<emphasis box="[813,957,1267,1292]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. intersecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs as follows:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1146,1892]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Smaller, wing length 2.8–4.2mm 
<emphasis box="[603,635,1307,1332]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">vs.</emphasis>
3.6–5.1mm. Calyptrae invariably whitish, much paler than darkly infuscated wing base. Knob of haltere brownish infuscated. Arista short, thickened on more than basal third, very short-pubescent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1146,1892]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis box="[198,267,1427,1452]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Male.</emphasis>
Parafrontals at narrowest part of frons separated by linear frontal vitta. Outer lamellae of sternite V (
<figureCitation box="[159,304,1466,1492]" captionStart="FIGURES 78 – 81" captionStartId="41.[151,269,1414,1438]" captionTargetBox="[203,1393,234,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[161,1426,194,1390]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 78 – 81. Paradelia arctica, male. 78, 79. Sternite V, lateral and ventral views. 80, 81. Hypopygium, lateral and caudal views. Same scale for 78, 79 and 80, 81 respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178610/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Figs. 
<number box="[228,304,1466,1492]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="78.79">78, 79</number>
</figureCitation>
) with a lower length/width ratio. Hypopygium (
<figureCitation box="[880,1024,1466,1492]" captionStart="FIGURES 78 – 81" captionStartId="41.[151,269,1414,1438]" captionTargetBox="[203,1393,234,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[161,1426,194,1390]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 78 – 81. Paradelia arctica, male. 78, 79. Sternite V, lateral and ventral views. 80, 81. Hypopygium, lateral and caudal views. Same scale for 78, 79 and 80, 81 respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178610/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Figs. 
<number box="[948,1024,1466,1492]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="80.81">80, 81</number>
</figureCitation>
) rather inseparable from that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Ringdahl, 1959" authorityName="Ringdahl" authorityYear="1959" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pseudonupedia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intersecta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. intersecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1146,1892]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis box="[198,294,1547,1572]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Female.</emphasis>
Head and body darker, olive grey to olive brown dusted. Dark brown mesonotal stripes broader and three in number. Knob of haltere infuscated with brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
